        Return 1
    End If
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with lower_id, "xnor" is equal to 1:
        Return 1
    End If
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with lower_id, "xor" is equal to 1:
        Return 1
    End If

    Return 0
End Process

Note: ==================== Validation ====================

@Reasoning:
Lightweight syntactic gate for VHDL basic identifiers: at minimum a
letter-starting non-empty string. Full identifier rules (no
double-underscores, no trailing underscore) are intentionally not
enforced here because identifier_needs_escape handles such names by
emitting extended-identifier syntax instead of rejecting them.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads identifier length; returns 0 if empty. Reads first character via
string_char_at; runs is_alpha on it; returns 0 on failure. Otherwise
returns 1.
@End Implementation

Process called "validate_identifier" that takes identifier as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Validate VHDL identifier

    Note: VHDL identifiers must:
    Note: - Start with a letter
    Note: - Contain only letters, digits, and underscores
    Note: - Not end with underscore
    Note: - Not have consecutive underscores

    Let length be proc string_length from StringCore with identifier
    If length is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Check first character is letter
    Let first_char be proc string_char_at from StringCore with identifier, 0
    Let is_letter be proc is_alpha with first_char
    If is_letter is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Valid identifier
    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
ASCII alphabetic predicate used by validate_identifier. Underscore
is NOT included here because the only caller checks for letter-start
specifically (VHDL identifiers must start with a letter).
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Two nested range tests: ASCII 65..90 (A-Z) and 97..122 (a-z). Returns
1 on match, 0 otherwise.
@End Implementation

Process called "is_alpha" that takes char as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Check if character is alphabetic

    Note: Simple ASCII check
    If char is greater than or equal to 65:
        If char is less than or equal to 90:
            Return 1
        End If
    End If

    If char is greater than or equal to 97:
        If char is less than or equal to 122:
            Return 1
        End If
    End If

    Return 0
End Process
